# Task: Android Database Layer with Room

## What to Build
Room database setup mirroring iOS GRDB implementation.

## Two-Database Architecture

### ContentDatabase.kt
@Database(
    entities = [PlaceEntity::class, PriceCardEntity::class, PhraseEntity::class, ...],
    version = 1,
    exportSchema = true
)
abstract class ContentDatabase : RoomDatabase() {
    abstract fun placeDao(): PlaceDao
    abstract fun priceCardDao(): PriceCardDao
    abstract fun phraseDao(): PhraseDao
    // ... other DAOs
}

### UserDatabase.kt
@Database(
    entities = [UserSettingEntity::class, FavoriteEntity::class, RecentEntity::class],
    version = 1,
    exportSchema = true
)
abstract class UserDatabase : RoomDatabase() {
    abstract fun userSettingsDao(): UserSettingsDao
    abstract fun favoritesDao(): FavoritesDao
    abstract fun recentsDao(): RecentsDao
}

### DatabaseManager.kt
@Singleton
class DatabaseManager @Inject constructor(
    @ApplicationContext private val context: Context
) {
    val contentDb: ContentDatabase by lazy { buildContentDatabase() }
    val userDb: UserDatabase by lazy { buildUserDatabase() }

    private fun buildContentDatabase(): ContentDatabase {
        // Copy from assets on first run
        // Open as read-only
    }

    private fun buildUserDatabase(): UserDatabase {
        // Create in app files directory
    }
}

## Entity Examples

### PlaceEntity.kt
@Entity(tableName = "places")
data class PlaceEntity(
    @PrimaryKey val id: String,
    val name: String,
    val aliases: String?,  // JSON array
    val category: String?,
    val shortDescription: String?,
    val lat: Double?,
    val lng: Double?,
    // ... all fields from schema
)

## TypeConverters

@TypeConverter
fun fromStringList(value: List<String>?): String? = 
    value?.let { Json.encodeToString(it) }

@TypeConverter
fun toStringList(value: String?): List<String>? =
    value?.let { Json.decodeFromString(it) }

## DAO Examples

@Dao
interface PlaceDao {
    @Query("SELECT * FROM places")
    fun getAll(): Flow<List<PlaceEntity>>

    @Query("SELECT * FROM places WHERE id = :id")
    suspend fun getById(id: String): PlaceEntity?

    @Query("SELECT * FROM places WHERE category = :category")
    fun getByCategory(category: String): Flow<List<PlaceEntity>>
}

## FTS Support
Room supports FTS4 out of the box:

@Entity
@Fts4(contentEntity = PlaceEntity::class)
data class PlaceFts(
    @ColumnInfo(name = "name") val name: String,
    @ColumnInfo(name = "short_description") val shortDescription: String
)

## First-Run Setup
1. Check if content.db exists in files dir
2. If not, copy from assets/seed/content.db
3. Open ContentDatabase read-only
4. Create UserDatabase if not exists

## Verification
- Databases initialize without crash
- Content queries return data
- User data persists across restarts
- FTS search works

# Task: Shared Engine Test Vectors

## What to Build
JSON test vector files that both iOS and Android test suites consume to verify engine implementations produce identical results.

## Why This Matters
The app's core value depends on consistent behavior:
- PricingEngine: Quote → Action fairness must be identical
- GeoEngine: Distance/bearing calculations must match
- Both platforms showing different results = broken trust

## Files to Create

### shared/tests/pricing-engine-vectors.json
Test cases for PricingEngine:
[
  {
    "name": "Basic fair price",
    "input": {
      "expectedMin": 20, "expectedMax": 40,
      "quotedMAD": 30,
      "modifiers": [],
      "quantity": 1,
      "highMultiplier": 1.25,
      "lowMultiplier": 0.75
    },
    "expected": {
      "fairness": "fair",
      "adjustedMin": 20,
      "adjustedMax": 40
    }
  },
  // 15-20 more cases covering:
  // - Low price (suspicious)
  // - High price
  // - Very high price
  // - With night modifier
  // - With multiple modifiers
  // - With quantity > 1
  // - Edge cases (exactly on boundary)
]

### shared/tests/geo-engine-vectors.json
Test cases for GeoEngine:
[
  {
    "name": "Haversine distance - Marrakech",
    "function": "haversine",
    "input": {
      "from": { "lat": 31.6258, "lng": -7.9891 },
      "to": { "lat": 31.6219, "lng": -7.9833 }
    },
    "expected": {
      "meters": 750,
      "tolerance": 10
    }
  },
  {
    "name": "Bearing north",
    "function": "bearing",
    "input": {
      "from": { "lat": 31.0, "lng": -8.0 },
      "to": { "lat": 32.0, "lng": -8.0 }
    },
    "expected": {
      "degrees": 0,
      "tolerance": 0.1
    }
  },
  // More cases for bearing, relativeAngle, formatDistance
]

### shared/tests/plan-engine-vectors.json (Optional)
More complex, may allow some variation:
[
  {
    "name": "Short history day",
    "input": {
      "availableMinutes": 240,
      "interests": ["history"],
      "pace": "standard"
    },
    "assertions": {
      "minStops": 2,
      "maxStops": 4,
      "totalMinutesMax": 240,
      "containsCategory": ["museum", "landmark"]
    }
  }
]

## Integration

### iOS Tests (XCTest)
func testPricingEngine() {
    let vectors = loadVectors("pricing-engine-vectors.json")
    for vector in vectors {
        let result = PricingEngine.evaluate(vector.input)
        XCTAssertEqual(result.fairness, vector.expected.fairness)
        // ... more assertions
    }
}

### Android Tests (JUnit)
@Test
fun testPricingEngine() {
    val vectors = loadVectors("pricing-engine-vectors.json")
    vectors.forEach { vector ->
        val result = PricingEngine.evaluate(vector.input)
        assertEquals(vector.expected.fairness, result.fairness)
    }
}

## CI Integration
- Tests run on every PR
- Failure blocks merge
- Both platforms must pass same vectors

# Task: iOS Tab Navigation

## What to Build
SwiftUI TabView with 5 tabs matching the product design.

## Tabs
1. Home (house.fill) — Quick actions, today's tip, saved items
2. Explore (binoculars.fill) — Browse places, landmarks, neighborhoods
3. Eat (fork.knife) — Restaurants and cafes
4. Prices (tag.fill) — Price cards and Quote → Action
5. More (ellipsis) — Darija, Itineraries, Tips, Culture, Settings

## Implementation

### ContentView.swift
struct ContentView: View {
    @State private var selectedTab: Tab = .home

    var body: some View {
        TabView(selection: $selectedTab) {
            HomeView()
                .tabItem { Label("Home", systemImage: "house.fill") }
                .tag(Tab.home)

            ExploreView()
                .tabItem { Label("Explore", systemImage: "binoculars.fill") }
                .tag(Tab.explore)

            EatView()
                .tabItem { Label("Eat", systemImage: "fork.knife") }
                .tag(Tab.eat)

            PricesView()
                .tabItem { Label("Prices", systemImage: "tag.fill") }
                .tag(Tab.prices)

            MoreView()
                .tabItem { Label("More", systemImage: "ellipsis") }
                .tag(Tab.more)
        }
    }
}

enum Tab: Hashable {
    case home, explore, eat, prices, more
}

### Placeholder Views
Each feature view should exist as a placeholder:
struct HomeView: View {
    var body: some View {
        NavigationStack {
            Text("Home")
                .navigationTitle("Home")
        }
    }
}

### Navigation Stacks
Each tab wraps its content in NavigationStack for drill-down:
- Explore → PlaceDetail
- Eat → PlaceDetail
- Prices → PriceCardDetail
- More → various sub-screens

## Platform-Native Rules
- Never customize tab bar appearance beyond theming
- Preserve standard touch targets
- Keep 5 tabs maximum (Apple HIG)
- Tab switching should be instant

## State Preservation
- Tab selection should persist across app restarts (UserDefaults)
- Navigation stacks reset on tab switch (standard iOS behavior)

## Verification
- All 5 tabs appear correctly
- Tab icons and labels display
- Tapping tabs switches content
- NavigationStack works for drill-down

# Task: Android Reusable Components

## What to Build
Shared Compose components matching iOS counterparts.

## Components to Create

### Card.kt
@Composable
fun ContentCard(
    modifier: Modifier = Modifier,
    title: String? = null,
    onClick: (() -> Unit)? = null,
    content: @Composable ColumnScope.() -> Unit
) {
    Card(
        modifier = modifier,
        onClick = onClick ?: {},
        colors = CardDefaults.cardColors(...)
    ) {
        Column(modifier = Modifier.padding(16.dp)) {
            title?.let { 
                Text(it, style = MaterialTheme.typography.titleMedium)
                Spacer(modifier = Modifier.height(8.dp))
            }
            content()
        }
    }
}

### Chip.kt
@Composable
fun CategoryChip(
    text: String,
    selected: Boolean = false,
    onClick: () -> Unit = {}
) {
    FilterChip(
        selected = selected,
        onClick = onClick,
        label = { Text(text) }
    )
}

### PriceTag.kt
@Composable
fun PriceTag(
    minMad: Int?,
    maxMad: Int?,
    modifier: Modifier = Modifier
) {
    Text(
        text = formatPriceRange(minMad, maxMad),
        style = MaterialTheme.typography.labelLarge,
        color = MaterialTheme.colorScheme.primary,
        modifier = modifier
    )
}

### SectionHeader.kt
@Composable
fun SectionHeader(
    title: String,
    actionText: String? = null,
    onAction: (() -> Unit)? = null
) {
    Row(
        modifier = Modifier.fillMaxWidth().padding(16.dp),
        horizontalArrangement = Arrangement.SpaceBetween,
        verticalAlignment = Alignment.CenterVertically
    ) {
        Text(title, style = MaterialTheme.typography.titleMedium)
        actionText?.let {
            TextButton(onClick = onAction ?: {}) {
                Text(it)
            }
        }
    }
}

### OfflineBanner.kt
@Composable
fun OfflineBanner(
    onDismiss: () -> Unit
) {
    Surface(
        color = MaterialTheme.colorScheme.surfaceVariant
    ) {
        Row(
            modifier = Modifier.fillMaxWidth().padding(8.dp),
            verticalAlignment = Alignment.CenterVertically
        ) {
            Icon(Icons.Filled.CloudOff, "Offline")
            Spacer(Modifier.width(8.dp))
            Text("Offline • Core guide still works")
            Spacer(Modifier.weight(1f))
            IconButton(onClick = onDismiss) {
                Icon(Icons.Filled.Close, "Dismiss")
            }
        }
    }
}

### SkeletonLoader.kt
@Composable
fun SkeletonLoader(
    modifier: Modifier = Modifier
) {
    // Shimmer effect placeholder
    Box(
        modifier = modifier
            .background(
                brush = shimmerBrush(),
                shape = MaterialTheme.shapes.medium
            )
    )
}

### ErrorState.kt
@Composable
fun ErrorState(
    message: String,
    onRetry: () -> Unit
) {
    Column(
        modifier = Modifier.fillMaxSize(),
        horizontalAlignment = Alignment.CenterHorizontally,
        verticalArrangement = Arrangement.Center
    ) {
        Icon(Icons.Filled.Error, "Error", tint = MaterialTheme.colorScheme.error)
        Spacer(Modifier.height(16.dp))
        Text(message)
        Spacer(Modifier.height(16.dp))
        Button(onClick = onRetry) { Text("Retry") }
    }
}

## Design Principles
- All components use MaterialTheme tokens
- Touch targets ≥48dp
- Proper content descriptions for TalkBack
- Support RTL layout
- Match iOS counterpart behavior

## Verification
- Components render in previews
- Theme colors apply correctly
- Accessibility labels work
- Components compose correctly

# Task: Android Bottom Navigation

## What to Build
Material 3 bottom navigation with 5 destinations matching iOS.

## Navigation Destinations
1. Home (Icons.Filled.Home)
2. Explore (Icons.Filled.Explore)
3. Eat (Icons.Filled.Restaurant)
4. Prices (Icons.Filled.LocalOffer)
5. More (Icons.Filled.MoreHoriz)

## Implementation

### NavGraph.kt
sealed class Screen(val route: String) {
    object Home : Screen("home")
    object Explore : Screen("explore")
    object Eat : Screen("eat")
    object Prices : Screen("prices")
    object More : Screen("more")

    // Detail screens
    object PlaceDetail : Screen("place/{placeId}")
    object PriceCardDetail : Screen("priceCard/{cardId}")
}

### BottomNavBar.kt
@Composable
fun BottomNavBar(
    navController: NavController,
    currentRoute: String?
) {
    NavigationBar {
        bottomNavItems.forEach { item ->
            NavigationBarItem(
                icon = { Icon(item.icon, contentDescription = item.label) },
                label = { Text(item.label) },
                selected = currentRoute == item.route,
                onClick = {
                    navController.navigate(item.route) {
                        popUpTo(navController.graph.startDestinationId)
                        launchSingleTop = true
                    }
                }
            )
        }
    }
}

### MainActivity.kt
@AndroidEntryPoint
class MainActivity : ComponentActivity() {
    override fun onCreate(savedInstanceState: Bundle?) {
        super.onCreate(savedInstanceState)
        enableEdgeToEdge()
        setContent {
            MarrakechGuideTheme {
                MainScreen()
            }
        }
    }
}

@Composable
fun MainScreen() {
    val navController = rememberNavController()
    val currentRoute = navController.currentBackStackEntryAsState().value?.destination?.route

    Scaffold(
        bottomBar = {
            BottomNavBar(navController, currentRoute)
        }
    ) { padding ->
        NavHost(
            navController = navController,
            startDestination = Screen.Home.route,
            modifier = Modifier.padding(padding)
        ) {
            composable(Screen.Home.route) { HomeScreen() }
            composable(Screen.Explore.route) { ExploreScreen() }
            composable(Screen.Eat.route) { EatScreen() }
            composable(Screen.Prices.route) { PricesScreen() }
            composable(Screen.More.route) { MoreScreen() }

            // Detail screens
            composable(Screen.PlaceDetail.route) { backStackEntry ->
                PlaceDetailScreen(backStackEntry.arguments?.getString("placeId"))
            }
        }
    }
}

## Predictive Back
Enable predictive back animation:
- AndroidManifest: android:enableOnBackInvokedCallback="true"
- Handle back in NavHost correctly

## Platform Rules
- Use Material 3 NavigationBar component
- Keep 5 items maximum
- Proper icons and labels
- Touch targets ≥48dp

## Verification
- All 5 destinations reachable
- Bottom bar highlights current tab
- Navigation state preserved on config change
- Back button works correctly
- Predictive back animation works
